ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: Timepoint/visit label
Notes: e.g., Baseline, 6-Month Follow Up, Year 2; Morning, At Bedtime

ElementDescription: AASPIRE Participant Type / Version Administered
Notes: 1= Direct Report (DR); 2= Direct Report - Supported (DR-S); 3= Caregiver Report (CR)

ElementDescription: Are the people from (Direct Report: your / Caregiver Report: their) developmental disability support agency who provide (your/their) support good at their jobs?
Notes: 1= Not at all; 2= A Little; 3= Moderately; 4= Mostly; 5= Totally

ElementDescription: Do the people from (Direct Report: your / Caregiver Report: their) developmental disability support agency who provide (your/their) support know enough about (your/their) condition or disability? For example, do they know enough about the problems or difficulties (you/they) experience to be able to support (you/them)?
Notes: 1= Not at all; 2= A Little; 3= Moderately; 4= Mostly; 5= Totally

ElementDescription: Do the people from (Direct Report: your / Caregiver Report: their) developmental disability support agency who provide (your/their) support meet (your/their) needs?
Notes: 1= Not at all; 2= A Little; 3= Moderately; 4= Mostly; 5= Totally

ElementDescription: Do the people from (Direct Report: your / Caregiver Report: their) developmental disability support agency who provide (your/their) support involve (you/them) in decisions about (your/their) services?
Notes: 1= Not at all; 2= A Little; 3= Moderately; 4= Mostly; 5= Totally

ElementDescription: Do the people from (Direct Report: your / Caregiver Report: their) developmental disability support agency who provide (your/their) support respect (your/their) wishes if (you/they) say (you/they) do not want some services?
Notes: 1= Not at all; 2= A Little; 3= Moderately; 4= Mostly; 5= Totally

ElementDescription: Do the people from (Direct Report: your / Caregiver Report: their) developmental disability support agency who provide (your/their) support communicate well with (you/them)?
Notes: 1= Not at all; 2= A Little; 3= Moderately; 4= Mostly; 5= Totally

ElementDescription: Satisfaction with Developmental Disability Services - Overall, in the last six months, did these things...
Notes: 1= Get worse; 2= Stay about the same; 3= Get better

ElementDescription: Overall, how would you rate the quality of services (Direct Report: you / Caregiver Report: they) get from (your/their) developmental disability services agency?
Notes: 1= Poor; 2= Fair; 3= Good; 4= Very good; 5= Excellent

ElementDescription: Do (Direct Report: you / Caregiver Report: they) have to wait a long time to see the people who provide (you/them) disability services and support? For example, does it take long to get appointments or visits?
Notes: 1= Not at all; 2= A Little; 3= Moderately; 4= Mostly; 5= Totally

ElementDescription: Does having to do all the necessary paperwork make it hard for (Direct Report: you / Caregiver Report: them) to get the disability services and support (you/they) need? For example, do (you/they or their caregivers) have to fill in lots of forms?
Notes: 1= Not at all; 2= A Little; 3= Moderately; 4= Mostly; 5= Totally

ElementDescription: Do (Direct Report: you / Caregiver Report: you think they or their caregivers) have to fight for the care and disability services and support (you/they) need?
Notes: 1= Not at all; 2= A Little; 3= Moderately; 4= Mostly; 5= Totally

ElementDescription: Do (Direct Report: you / Caregiver Report: they) have a hard time getting the disability services and support (you/they) need because they are not available? For example, there is a lack of facilities, staff, services, or programs in their area.
Notes: 1= Not at all; 2= A Little; 3= Moderately; 4= Mostly; 5= Totally

ElementDescription: Overall, in the last six months, how hard (Direct Report: was it / Caregiver Report: do you think it is for them) to get disability services and supports...
Notes: 1= Get worse; 2= Stay about the same; 3= Get better

ElementDescription: Miscellaneous comments on study, interview, methodology relevant to this form data
Disability Services Satisfaction - Sum
Notes: Higher numbers indicate more satisfaction with disability services. Sum of (dssat_good, dssat_informed, dssat_needs, dssat_involved, dssat_respect, dssat_communicate, dssat_waittime, dssat_paperwork, dssat_fightfor, dssat_get_services)

ElementDescription: Disability Services Satisfaction - Average
Notes: Higher numbers indicate more satisfaction with disability services. Mean of non-missing responses from (dssat_good, dssat_informed, dssat_needs, dssat_involved, dssat_respect, dssat_communicate, dssat_waittime, dssat_paperwork, dssat_fightfor, dssat_get_services)
